               <p>other things—I said I would bave it, and I gave him 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. deposit—he said I should have all the fruit in the garden—<hi rend="italic">from</hi> the 10th to the 21st of July I purchased to the amount of 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I paid him for every thing as I fetched it away—I am quite sure I had to that amount—the whole amount I had was 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. altogether, up to the 25th of July.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you lived where you do? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two months, under Mr. Gardner—I worked before for Mr. Finch, a carpenter, at Wimbledon—I bave been a bricklayer's laboured a carpenter's labourer—I have no account of the sale <hi rend="italic">of</hi> this fruit—I took it as I take it in Covent-garden, and paid for it—what I had between the 10th and the 21st of July was 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I think I am wrong in that ststemet, it was 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. Is went to the prisoner, after the major had come bow, but I did not know it—I then wanted some fruit, which the prisoner refuted to let me have—I had been there a few days before, and he said there were ax half sieves of red and black currants; and when I went, he said I wts to have the last, and that was all, and be would not let me go into the ganfca to see—he pushed me out, as if I was not to dare to go in—he once wanted me to buy some hay—I asked him to let me have a bit for a sample, that I might show it to somebody that knew it better than myself—he said be bad shsj* stack to sell, and be bad a borse to sell, and Major Sbeppard wanted lit if it—I did not give him a shilling for the little bit of bay—he refused to itf me have it—I have a stable—I did not ask him to let roe bave a few ateos to pave it—I did not say that I would be d—d if I would not <hi rend="italic">do</hi> for him—I told him the last time, when he sold me only one half-sieve, that fld <hi rend="italic">pull</hi> him to Wands worth, because the agreement was, I should have all fruit in the garden; and the last week be would not let me go I garden, to see what there was.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You did not keep an account of the exact smut you paid him day by day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I hare no doubt whaterer that I felt prisoner 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. altogether for Major Sheppard.</p>
